answers.body_markdown:
Your program is reading off the end of allocated memory. In your `create` method, you do not allocate enough space to store an entire row of elements:

```c++
void Matrix::create(int r,int c)
{
    row=r;
    col=c;
    ptr=new int* [row];
    static srand(time(0));
    for(int i=0;i&lt;row;++i)
    {
        ptr[i]=new int[i+1]; // &lt;- the allocation is here
    }
    for(int i=0;i&lt;row;i++)
    {
        for(int j=0;j&lt;col;j++) // &lt;- you iterate j from 0 to col here
        {
            ptr[i][j]=rand()%6+1; // &lt;- and then access here
        }
    }
}
```

Since you are allocating i+1 elements, the first row only has enough space for a single element, the second has space for two and so on. Modifying the allocation to make space for `col` elements should fix the issue.

